# Production-ready changes

Treat work as **merge- and deploy-ready** only when the items below are satisfied (or explicitly called out as out of scope).

## Correctness and acceptance

- **Behavior:** Functionality matches intent; edge cases the change touches are considered.
- **Tests:** `pnpm test` passes. New or updated tests reflect **acceptance criteria** / the business case—not only “green locally.”
- **Bugs:** Prefer catching issues **before** production: tests, manual checks on `pnpm serve`, and review of user-visible paths in `public/`.

## Code quality

- **Readable and maintainable:** Names, structure, and comments match the rest of the repo; avoid clever one-offs without need.
- **Backward compatibility (no-break):** Prefer changes that don’t break existing users, data shapes, or Firestore paths unless the task is an intentional migration (then document in commit/PR).

## Security

- No new **XSS** vectors (escape or safe DOM APIs for user content), no widening **Firestore rules** without justification, no secrets in client code. Align with [firestore.rules](firestore.rules) and [CLAUDE.md](CLAUDE.md).

## Rollback and traceability

- **Rollback:** Keep changes **small and focused** so `git revert` (or redeploying a prior Hosting version) is realistic. Avoid mixing unrelated refactors with fixes.
- **Traceability:** Commit messages (and PR descriptions when used) should make **investigation** easy: what changed, why, and how to verify.
